ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Interconnection Details. Sections 2(b)-(f) of Appendix C of the LGIA are incorporated by reference herein. 2.2 Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Phase owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant’s successors or assigns) at the Lamont Substation. Each Co-Tenant shall have an undivided ownership interest as tenant-in-common in the rights and obligations of the Interconnection Customer and the LGIA equal to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, and possess an undivided right to enjoy all of such interest in the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. 2.3 Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Phase to the Lamont Substation to the extent such interconnection will result in such Co-Tenant having a Phase with a Net Nameplate Capacity in excess of the Interconnection Capacity allocated to such Phase in the LGIA. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Phase in excess of its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Phase so as not to exceed its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the Interconnection Capacity. 2.4 Curtailment. In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction of CAISO or Participating TO, such curtailment shall be allocated pro rata among the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest; provided, however, that the Manager shall only curtail on a non-pro rata basis if (a) with respect to any curtailment of an amount less than 5 megawatts and for a limited duration not to exceed 6 hours, it reasonably determines that non-pro rata allocation of such curtailment is necessary with respect to the prudent operation of the Redwood Solar Farm Project (so long as it does not select one Phase more often than the other Phase in allocation of any such curtailment) or (b) such allocation is necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each case, that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA or any PPA to which a Co-Tenant is a party. 2.5 LGIA Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the periodic payment of all expenses incurred under the LGIA in accordance with its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest, as provided below: (a) Interconnection Customer’s Construction Costs. (b) Participating TO’s Construction Costs. (i) Reimbursable Construction Costs. (ii) Non-reimbursable Construction Costs. (c) LGIA Operating Expenses. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the LGIA Operating Expenses according to such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest. (d) Payment of LGIA Expenses. The Manager shall, as authorized agent for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection and payment of the LGIA Operating Expenses, Participating TO’s Construction Costs, and other amounts due from the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant obligated to pay LGIA Operating Expenses, Participating TO’s Construction Costs and other amounts under the LGIA shall pay each invoice for such costs and amounts promptly upon receipt of written notice thereof from the Manager, but in any event within thirty (30) days of such receipt or such earlier time as required by the LGIA. 2.6 Liquidated Damages; Credits, Reimbursements, Refunds. To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits, reimbursements or refunds pursuant to the LGIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits, reimbursements or refunds to the Co-Tenants, except for 54KR, according to such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest adjusted to exclude 54KR as follows: (i) 28.57% for 67RK, (ii) 45.71% for 65HK and (iii) 25.71% for 87RL (unless such damages, credits, reimbursements or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). 2.7 Joint and Several Liability. Each Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LGIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LGIA; provided, however, that each Party shall be severally, and not, jointly liable for all other obligations hereunder. 2.8 Projected Capacity. Each Co-Tenant shall notify the Manager and the other Co-Tenants in writing, no later than thirty (30) days before such Co-Tenant’s Construction Commencement Date, of the Net Nameplate Capacity of its Phase, provided that each Co-Tenant’s Net Nameplate Capacity is subject to Section 2.3 and may not exceed such Co-Tenant’s Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity. 2.9 Indemnity. (a) Each Co-Tenant (an “Indemnifying Co-Tenant”) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants (each, an “Indemnified Co-Tenant”) from and against any and all losses (including all lost revenues under applicable PPAs), damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys’ and consultants’ fees (collectively, “Claims”), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant in connection with any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to Manager as agent for the Co-Tenants under the LGIA, and shall provide Manager such information required by Manager to comply with its obligations (including Interconnection Customer’s obligations) under the LGIA. (d) With respect to jointly held assets, the Co-Tenants may delegate to the Manager some or all of their respective obligations under this Agreement. 2.12 Events of Default; Default. The following shall constitute “Events of Default”: a Party fails to perform its obligations under this Agreement or the LGIA in any material respect, and such Party fails to cure such default within (i) ten (10) days after receipt of written notice of a payment default, or (ii) twenty (20) days after receipt of written notice of any non-payment default, provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations other than a payment default is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then such Co-Tenant shall not be in default under this Section 2.12 if it commences to cure such default within twenty (20) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed sixty (60) days, including the initial cure period. 2.13 Remedies. Subject to the last sentence of Section 5.8, in addition to all other remedies permitted by Law or under this Agreement (all of which shall be cumulative), following an Event of Default, each non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, to perform the obligations of the defaulting Party, and the defaulting Party shall reimburse the performing Parties for their expenses which they incurred in rendering the performance, plus interest at the Interest Rate. 2.14 Disconnection. (a) If a Co-Tenant fails to cure any default of it under this Agreement or the LGIA within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of such default, the Manager may disconnect the breaching Co-Tenant’s Phase from the Lamont Substation (i) after obtaining written approval to do so from a Majority of the Co-Tenants then not in default; provided, that in the event that the calculation of the voting of the Co-Tenants then not in default results in a tie and a Majority of the Co-Tenants then not in default cannot be achieved, only the consent of the Manager shall be required to constitute a Majority of the Co-Tenants under this clause (i), or (ii) without approval from the Co-Tenants then not in default but only to the extent necessary to prevent or cure a “Default” under the LGIA; provided if the nature of the defaulted obligation or obligations is such that more than thirty (30) days are required, in the exercise of commercially reasonable diligence, for cure of such default, then the Manager may not disconnect the defaulting Co-Tenant’s Phase if such Co-Tenant commences to cure such default within twenty five (25) days after receiving notice of the default and thereafter continuously pursues the same to completion with commercially reasonable diligence, such extended period not to exceed eighty five (85) days, including the initial cure period; provided further, that in no event shall any cure period hereunder extend beyond any applicable cure period under the LGIA. (b) To the extent caused by a Co-Tenant’s default hereunder, the Manager may also disconnect such Co-Tenant’s Phase in order to prevent damage to the other Co-Tenants’ Phases, the Interconnection Facilities or the property of the Participating TO or as otherwise needed to prevent or mitigate technical issues affecting the Phases; the Manager shall immediately notify the Co-Tenants of any such disconnection. 2.15 Equitable Relief. The Parties agree that damages may be an inadequate remedy for a breach by the Manager or any other Party of its respective obligations under this Agreement, and that each Party shall be entitled to seek injunctive and other equitable relief, including specific performance, against any other Party or the Manager to prevent or eliminate such default. 2.16 Dispute Resolution. (a) Submission. In the event any Party has a dispute, or asserts a claim, that arises out of or in connection with this Agreement or the LGIA, such Party (the “Disputing Party”) shall provide the other Parties with written notice of the dispute or claim (“Notice of Dispute”). Such dispute or claim shall be referred to a designated senior representative of each Party for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable after receipt of the Notice of Dispute by the Parties. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the claim or dispute through unassisted or assisted negotiations within thirty (30) days of the other Parties’ receipt of the Notice of Dispute, such claim or dispute may, upon mutual agreement of the Parties, be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth below. In the event the Parties do not agree within such thirty (30) day period to submit such claim or dispute to arbitration, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or at law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. (b) Arbitration Procedures. Any arbitration initiated under this Agreement shall be conducted before a single neutral arbitrator appointed by the Parties. The arbitrator shall be knowledgeable in electric utility matters, including electric transmission and bulk power issues, and shall not have any current or past substantial business or financial relationships with any party to the arbitration (except prior arbitration). The arbitrator shall provide each of the Parties an opportunity to be heard and, except as otherwise provided herein, shall conduct the arbitration in accordance with the rules and procedures for arbitration of complex business disputes for Judicial Arbitration and Mediation Services, Inc. (“Arbitration Rules”) and any applicable FERC regulations; provided, however, in the event of a conflict between the Arbitration Rules and the terms of this Section 2.16, the terms of this Section 2.16 shall prevail. (c) Arbitration Decisions. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, the arbitrator shall render a decision within ninety (90) days of appointment and shall notify the Parties in writing of such decision and the reasons therefor. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and the LGIA and shall have no power to modify or change any provision of such agreements in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon the Parties, and judgment on the award may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The decision of the arbitrator may be appealed solely on the grounds that the conduct of the arbitrator, or the decision itself, violated the standards set forth in the Federal Arbitration Act or the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act. The final decision of the arbitrator must also be filed with FERC if it affects jurisdictional rates, terms and conditions of service, Interconnection Facilities, or Network Upgrades. (d) Costs. Each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for its own costs incurred during the arbitration process and for such Co-Tenant’s Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest of the cost of the arbitrator chosen, if applicable. 2.17 Effect of Force Majeure. If, because of an event of Force Majeure, any Party is unable to carry out its obligations under this Agreement, and if such Party promptly gives the other Parties written notice of such Force Majeure in detail, specifying the nature, extent and expected duration of such Force Majeure, the non-payment obligations and liabilities of the Party giving such notice and the corresponding obligations and liabilities of any other Party shall be temporarily suspended to the extent made necessary by and during the continuance of such Force Majeure; provided, that in no event will the suspension of a Party’s obligations and liabilities hereunder be permitted to cause a “Default” under the LGIA. Any disabling effects of such event of Force Majeure shall be eliminated as soon as and to the extent reasonably practicable by the Party claiming Force Majeure. 2.18 Notice of Default. Each Co-Tenant and the Manager shall promptly provide written notice to the other Parties upon receiving notice of, or otherwise discovering, any default or potential default under this Agreement or the LGIA or receiving any other notice under the LGIA. 2.19 Generator Downsizing Process. The Parties acknowledge and agree that, prior to the Effective Date, the Commercial Operation Dates for the 65HK Phase, the 67RK Phase and the 87RL Phase have occurred at the Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity as set forth on Exhibit A for each such Phase. In the event that the Commercial Operation Date with respect to the 54KR Phase is reached and such Phase has a total megawatt capacity amount that is lower than the amount specified in the LGIA by an amount greater than the de minimis threshold of Appendix DD of the CAISO Tariff, the Manager shall submit (on behalf of 54KR), a completed Generator Downsizing Request application and deposit with respect to the uncompleted capacity of such Phase to the CAISO during the last Generator Downsizing Request Window applicable to such Phase. 54KR will be responsible for payment of all deposits and other obligations for study costs, executing agreements required by CAISO in the Generator Downsizing Process, all costs to amend the LGIA and any other costs incurred in connection with the Generator Downsizing Process. If the Interconnection Capacity is reduced as a result of the Generator Downsizing Process, the Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity shall be reduced only with respect to the 54KR Phase. If the Interconnection Capacity is reduced for any reason other than as a result of the Generator Downsizing Process, the 54KR Phase shall automatically be reduced in proportion to its Co-Tenancy Percentage Interest by an amount equal to the difference between 90 MW and the revised Interconnection Capacity. If the Maximum Net Nameplate Capacity of a Co-Tenant’s Phase is reduced to zero, such Co-Tenant will be automatically removed as a Party hereunder, provided that such Co-Tenant will remain liable for any obligations incurred hereunder prior to such removal. ARTICLE III MANAGER 3.1 Appointment of Manager; Manager Services. Each Co-Tenant hereby appoints the Manager to act as its agent and representative for all purposes under the LGIA, and, unless otherwise agreed by a Majority of the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA and shall coordinate compliance with the LGIA by the Co-Tenants; provided that the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer the LGIA or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under the LGIA or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under the LGIA, without the prior written consent of a Majority of the Co-Tenants; provided further that if any such termination, amendment, Transfer, waiver or settlement would disproportionately and materially adversely affect a Co-Tenant in comparison to the other Co-Tenants, then, unless such dissimilar treatment is not otherwise justified in accordance with prudent operating and utility industry practices, such Co-Tenant’s prior written consent will be required. In addition, each Co-Tenant specifically authorizes the Manager to negotiate and, with a Majority of the Co-Tenants’ prior written consent, execute on its behalf and on behalf of the Interconnection Customer, and agrees to be bound by the terms of, a retail electricity service agreement; provided that, to the extent that the Manager acts as agent for the Co-Tenants under any such agreement, the Manager may not terminate, amend or Transfer any such agreement or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under any such agreement or initiate or settle any dispute resolution under any such agreement, without the prior written consent of a Majority of the Co-Tenants; provided that if any such termination, amendment, Transfer, waiver, initiation or settlement would disproportionately and materially adversely affect a Co-Tenant in comparison to the other Co-Tenants, then, unless such dissimilar treatment is not otherwise justified in accordance with prudent operating and utility industry practices, such Co-Tenant’s prior written consent will be required. The Manager shall be the single point of contact between the Co-Tenants, on the one hand, and the CAISO and the Participating TO, on the other hand, and shall be responsible for all administrative obligations of the Interconnection Customer under the LGIA, including billing, issuing payments, providing notices and communicating with, and receiving instructions from, the CAISO and the Participating TO with respect to the Phases and the LGIA. (a) Maintenance or Records. The Manager shall maintain books and records in sufficient detail to verify amounts due and payable hereunder for a period of not less than three (3) years after the end of the calendar month to which they relate, and all such books and records shall be available for inspection and/or copying by each Co-Tenant or its authorized representative at the cost and expense of such Co-Tenant and at reasonable times during regular business hours, upon reasonable notice to the Manager. (b) Provision of Records. The Manager shall, from time to time or at the reasonable request of the Co-Tenants or their Financing Parties, provide reports to the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties sufficient to keep the Co-Tenants and their Financing Parties reasonably apprised as to significant matters concerning the LGIA, the Construction Costs and the LGIA Operating Expenses. 3.5 Replacement of Manager. Upon the written approval of a Majority of the Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenants may replace the Manager with any Person of their choosing. Upon any replacement of the then-existing Manager, the then-existing Manager shall no longer be a Party hereunder and the new Manager appointed by the Co-Tenants shall be the Manager hereunder. The new Manager shall execute a joinder to this Agreement and provide its contact information pursuant to Section 5.1. 3.6 Management Fee. In consideration of the services provided by Manager hereunder, the Manager shall be paid an annual fee of twelve thousand Dollars ($12,000.00) (the “Management Fee”), payable monthly, in advance, in equal monthly installments, beginning on the date hereof and ending on the termination of this Agreement or the replacement of the Manager. Notwithstanding any other provision herein to the contrary (other than Section 2.4, 2.5, 2.6, 2.14 and 2.19), the Manager shall not Discriminate in providing services or otherwise performing its obligations hereunder among the Co-Tenants. The Manager shall perform its obligations under this Agreement (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with good operating and utility industry practices, (c) in compliance with all applicable Laws, including but not limited to the FPA, and all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FPA, (d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LGIA. 3.9 Termination of LGIA.
